data.content:
These tests are already in good shape — factory method, `DataRow` parameterization, and clean AAA structure. A few suggestions:

**1. Repeated magic strings** — `"user@example.com"` and `"admin"` appear 4+ times. Extract constants:
```csharp
private const string DefaultEmail = "user@example.com";
private const string DefaultRole = "admin";
```

**2. Brittle time assertion** — `token.ExpiresAt > DateTime.UtcNow` uses wall-clock time instead of the `FakeClock` you're already injecting. If the token's expiry is derived from the fake clock, assert against it:
```csharp
Assert.AreEqual(expectedExpiry, token.ExpiresAt);
```
This also makes the test deterministic rather than timing-sensitive.

**3. `CreateTokenService` can be simplified:**
```csharp
private static TokenService CreateTokenService(TimeSpan? clockOffset = null)
{
    var clock = new FakeClock(DateTimeOffset.UtcNow + (clockOffset ?? TimeSpan.Zero));
    return new TokenService(clock, new InMemoryTokenStore());
}
```

**Overall verdict:** This is a well-structured, maintainable test class. The factory method and parameterized tests will make future changes easy. The magic strings and wall-clock assertion are the main things to tighten up.
